A single test was carried out on cells of this type, a proprietary chemistry understood to be lithium nickel cobalt aluminium (NCA). These cells have a high nominal capacity of 2900mAh but a relatively short rated cycle life. The pack cycled normally (Fig. 10
                           ) until Cells 1 and 8 started to register anomalies around Cycle 300 (Fig. 11
                           ) which were similar to those exhibited by Cell 1 in Test 3.

This test used a proprietary chemistry understood to be NMC. The pack performed normally for 300 cycles at which point pack capacity was 1737mAh (83 % of rated capacity) with no evidence of cell drift (Fig. 12
                           ). At cycle 20, the spread of cell voltages at the end of PCR was 15 mV and this was unchanged at Cycle 500. At this point, however, several cells were starting to degrade, the effect of which was obvious by Cycle 600 (Fig. 13
                           ). At this point the CCeV phase had lengthened and although the cell voltages were largely aligned after PCR they diverged widely under discharge. Note that Cell 1 was a high outlier on charge and a low outlier on discharge, indicating that the issue was cell degradation rather than loss of balance. Further degradation led to the test being terminated after 638 cycles.

The cells behaved as expected for the initial 98 cycles at room temperature. Slightly raised internal impedance was evident from the outset in Cells 5,7 and 8, but this was fully accommodated by the CCeV charge algorithm (Fig. 15
                           ). PCR and PDR voltages remained closely aligned, indicating no cell drift at this point. When the ambient temperature gradient was introduced (Fig. 16
                           ), measured pack capacity immediately fell slightly, which is an expected consequence of the rapid (0.8C) discharge rate combined with the more sluggish kinetics associated with low temperature [37]. Although the colder cells exhibited higher voltages on CC charge and lower voltages on discharge, the PCR and PDR voltages remained closely aligned throughout the subsequent 150 cycles, indicating that the CCeV charge algorithm was fully accommodating the effect of the temperature gradient.

There was a modest degradation-related decline in capacity during this period but from Cycle 300 onward, approaching the cells' estimated cycle life at these low temperatures, the cold cells degraded very rapidly. Fig. 17
                            shows how the voltages traces had clearly separated into three groupings. Cells 6 and 7 on the inside of the refrigerated pack were deteriorating at very similar rates. Cells 5 and 8, which were colder than Cells 6 and 7 and subject to a temperature gradient on the outside of the pack, were deteriorating more rapidly, again at similar rates to each other. Pack capacity fell steeply from around 70 % at Cycle 350 to 5 % by Cycle 500 (Fig. 18
                           ) The test was terminated at 719 cycles.

These observations are consistent with the two-stage degradation pattern for NMC cells discussed in Section 2.3 
                           [25,26]. Close examination of the CCeV phase at Cycle 500, (Fig. 19
                           ), at which point pack capacity was down to about 5 % of nominal, shows that the degraded cells were at or close to V
                              limit
                            during most of the CCeV phase, falling away as the charge current dropped to low levels and during PCR. Tracing the PCR voltage history (Fig. 20
                           ), it can be seen that cell drift does not become detectable until after Cycle 300 and its emergence is clearly associated with the rapidly accelerating degradation of the cells (Fig. 18). By Cycle 350, with pack capacity down to about 70 %, the PCR voltage spread was still very small at around 30 mV. By contrast, an increasingly large voltage rebound during PDR can be seen in comparing Fig. 17 and Fig. 19. This implies that increased impedance, especially in Cells 5 and 8, is the major cause of the loss of usable pack capacity at the 0.9C discharge rate while PCR voltage drift, though detectable in the late stages of cell degradation, is of only secondary importance.
